segments.text: And so it was, back then the core voted in such a block anyway that it would have been hard and civilians didn't come to the polls for some reason.
And, but that allowed me to cut into a lot of the civilian student body vote and as a result of it kind of.
Now we'll get back to that year as student body president.
Let's go back to academics.
you're in class, what did you and your buddies think was the, were the guidelines for class attendance and conduct and so forth?
Oh, gosh, you know, the first couple years, we all thought, boy, you got to be there every time or the devil will swoop down on you and haul you off.
By the time we were juniors, we kind of got the impression, you don't necessarily have to be at every one of them if you have somebody else that can
help you take notes and stuff like that.
But for the first couple years, I mean, I think attendance was pretty serious.
Plus, the folks in your outfit, the upperclassmen, grades were then becoming a big deal.
Your outfit could go away if you didn't have them and stuff like that.
And so they made us study each night.
What about being awake in class?
Um...
Yeah, I never did have too much problem with that.

There was a bunch of dozers, though, guys in the Corps that, and maybe I wasn't in an outfit that, you know, did stuff like that, but we, I mean, lights went off at 10 o'clock or something in our outfit or, you know, like that, so we didn't have too much trouble with that, but there were, I remember there were a lot of professors upset, particularly with fish in the Corps who seemed to
be snoring a little bit in class, particularly the big classes like biology, zoology, and places like that where they might have, it seemed to me, four or five hundred kids in it.
Did you, in the first year or two, did you have any courses that were really tough to pass?
Everybody thought English was a tough course.
I never thought English was a very tough course.
I don't know.
I thought
I was horrible at math.
I had to do the remedial deal and the whole bit.
Which I'm sure is why I became the chief financial officer of the state of Texas.
I learned to hire good math people.
But math was real hard for me.
That's why I'm glad I went into political science instead of something that required an awful lot of math.
So I worked real hard to steer clear of math and chemistry and stuff like that.
Foreign languages were tough for me.
When I discovered that I had to have four semesters of foreign language, I went into a Spanish class
and everybody there was named Rodriguez, and I said, this ain't the place for me.
And so I went in a French class, and everybody there was named Dubois, and I said, that's not the place for me.
And I walked into a Russian class, and I thought, there's only one guy here named George Zaychevsky that can speak this stuff.
I'm starting on the same level as everybody else, and so I did.
The lucky thing for me
At the end of the first class period, the professor, his name was John Skravanek, and he was asking everybody, he said, you know, where are you from and all this kind of stuff.
And it's a true story.
This sounds unbelievable.
But it's the reason I stayed in the class.
He asked me, he said, where are you from?
And I said, I'm from Placido, Texas.
He said, Placido, Texas?
Where is that?
He said, that's in Victoria County, isn't it?
And I said, that's amazing.
You know where Placido, Texas is?
And he said, listen, when I was at the University of Texas teaching Czech, and he taught that here too, the best student I ever had in my life was from Placido, Texas.
And I said, really?
That's amazing.
He said, what was his name?
He said, it was a her.
I said, well, what was her name?
He said, Venus Mark.
And I said, that's my mother.
It's a true story.
I said, you've got to be kidding me.
And I tell him, he said, that's your mother?
I said, yeah, Venus Marks.
She married Melbourne Sharp, and I'm her youngest son.
And he said, that is absolutely amazing.
Let's go call your mother.
So we go over there, and we call mom and said, mom, who is your Czech teacher?
at the University of Texas, and you better get this right."
And she said, oh, Dr. John Skravanek, he was a great teacher.
Of course, mother spoke Czech before she spoke English.
And he gets on the phone and all this kind of stuff, and so I'm thinking I had a little help as I wormed my way through Russian.
And probably your second year, you had Gary Halter.
What made him special in your academic life?
Oh, because Gary just loved politics and he loved to talk about politics and he loved to talk about it in class and outside of class.
I wrote a paper one time and they asked us to talk about, I guess Watergate maybe was going on that particular time, and they asked us to analyze a political figure and I wrote this paper.
I hope I've lost it by now.
comparing Nixon to Hitler, and I found striking similarities.
That raised Halter's eyebrows a little bit, but, you know, I don't know.
And you turned to, what kind of advice did he give you?
It wasn't about politics, but he just, he gives me much more political advice now on things.
But then he talked about, we didn't talk about careers because
I don't think any of us were thinking about running for stuff back then, although it's amazing how that group all did.
I guess we couldn't get jobs in the private sector.
But he would talk to me about courses that he thought were interesting and stuff like that, and we'd talk about politics some, but just in terms of what was existing that particular day.
I don't think we talked about, hey, when you get out of school, you ought to
think about this or that, or run for something.
If you were wondering what courses to take, I'd always go to him.
You'd go to him.
And as you look back, his advice was good advice.
Yeah, I think good advice.
He helped me a lot.
How was it better to be a sophomore at A&M than to be a freshman?
Whoa, whoa, in the Corps, it was just night and day.
I mean, you know, granted you weren't out of the woods yet, but
and the pressure to me, I mean some of the kids would say,
It's the physical stuff, but the mental stuff, I just never got used to anybody screaming at me and telling me what a lowlife I was and all this kind of stuff.
It wasn't until years later that you kind of look back and appreciate what that was.
I'm not sure the people doing it.
It's just in the system and it takes you, it really strips you of your pride and everything else and then you have to kind of build it back as you're
as you're doing that with other folks.
But the sophomore year was remarkably different.
The junior year, I remember the feeling of taking my shoes off and walking on grass my senior year and thinking what an amazing feeling this is to be able to walk on something other than cement.
Were there, in those days, were there any easy courses that were kind of legendary for making grades?
Yeah, there were some jock courses.
You had to figure out which ones the jocks took.
And I never did a very good job of figuring those out.
I just heard about them.
But apparently there were some, at the time there were some economics courses and a couple other things that football players at the time knew which ones to take.
I got in one of those.
one time, which I thought was kind of... Did it turn out to be an easy?
It turned out to be pretty easy.
Yeah.
At the final exam, the professor left and locked the door.
I thought that was kind of interesting.
I'm sitting back here thinking, this guy's got video cameras.
You guys better quit doing all this stuff.
I never partook in it because I thought it was a sting operation or something like that.
It wasn't.
Were there any courses that were supposedly highly respected that you and your colleagues heard about, hey, this is a course you ought to take?
Yeah.
That was an option for us?
Yeah.
Yeah.
Some economics courses.
A guy named Ashcroft.
Ashcroft was history.
Was it history?
Ashcroft was history?
Yeah.
Well, it wasn't Graham.
I know Graham thinks that I took a course
under him, but I never did have that.
I didn't know Phil until after I'd already graduated.
But there was some economics course.
I guess I can't remember who the professor was.
As you look back on your four years here... And there was a literary course, Great Books it was called, that I thought was exceptional.
Somebody told me it was.
It was really good.
Do you remember who?
I don't remember.
It was a lady.
As you look back, who were the celebrity students while you were here?
Oh, gosh.
Well, when I was a freshman, when I was a fish, it was Hector Gutierrez.
I mean, he was commander of the Corps, and he carried himself like he was commander of the Corps.
And I remember him kind of walking along with his four diamonds, and everybody pretty much thought that's either God or
right-hand aid, you know, to him or something like that, so.
Did you all become acquainted?
No.
Didn't know him at all.
I was just a fish in the Corps.
We're good friends now, but I didn't, I didn't know him at all.
Was the fact that he was Hispanic and Corps Commander, did the, the fact that he was Minard, did that matter to anybody?
Uh, I don't, that wouldn't have registered on me because the class I came from was 90 percent, you know, the high school and grade school I came from was
a majority Hispanic and so it wouldn't have... Like what little I know about the way things were done then, I had the impression that Hector was selected for one reason, that he was the best.
The fact he was Hispanic was totally coincidental.
Yeah, I think that's probably right.
It was probably true of Henry the year before.
I didn't know Cisneros because he graduated in May of 68 and was a White House fellow and I came in the fall of 68.
So I didn't know Henry until years later.
other celebrity students in your four years?
Oh, in the whole four years?
Well, I don't know.
Lane Cruz was one.
He was a class below me.
He was a Rhodes Scholar.
And he kind of followed me on everything political.
He was the student life chairman after I was and became the student body president after me.
Literally almost ran for everything that I ran.
We were real close friends.
And so you actually had a group of folks there that sometimes were on opposite sides.
Caperton started this deal called the Fifth Wheel.
And I was one of the few, me and a guy named Nick Jigger, were the only two Corps members that were in that deal.
And some of my friends in the Corps didn't like that deal.
that very much wound up to be a pretty good deal when I was a senior because I met a lot of civilian students and as well as people in the Corps.
So you had, gosh you had, in that student senate, my junior and senior year, you had Jerry Geisweit, who became a state representative from Mason.
You had Kent Caperton, who became a state senator from Bryan.
He had Gary Morrow, who became land commissioner for 16 years or however long he was.
Chet wasn't here yet, was he?
Who's that?
Chet Edwards.
Chet, sure was.
He was a class below me.
But Chet was in the Student Senate, but became real big in Skona.
Chet did his doing the MSC, and I would have named Chet.
Hackney was a member of the Student Senate, became a state representative from
From Houston, Perry became a state representative from Haskell, then Land Commissioner, then Lieutenant Governor.
There's a bunch more.
What was the stimulus?
I don't know.
I don't think any of us have ever been able to figure it out.
If you look at before that class, that two or three year group of people,
you can count the number of people, the number of Aggies that were in the Texas legislature on your fingers.
I mean, there's just Bill Moore, Peyton McKnight, Babe Swartz, and kind of Dick Slack.
I mean, just every now and then.
But all of a sudden, but that particular class, it's like everybody that was in the student senate went home and ran for something and got elected.
Now, does Wayne Stark deserve any credit for some of that?
He certainly did with Chet.
He was real close to Chet and real close to Randy Ross and folks like that.
He was a good friend of mine, but Wayne didn't much advise the Senate so much as he did the MSC.
I was in a bunch of those clubs in the MSC, but I never went that way like Kirk Hawkins did and some of those guys with the MSC.
Wayne...
I went on a trip that Wayne asked me to go to one time.
It was a skiing trip.
One winter, 300 of us went to Chamonix, France.
But on the way over, six of us in the back of the plane gathered.
Apparently, there were just six of us that had never seen snow since the seventh grade, much less skied on it.
And so we decided that we're going to land in Geneva, and we're going to rent a car, and we're going to go touring Europe for eight days, and we'll meet you guys back here when you got back.
And we barely made it back in time, and the plane was fueled, ready to go, and they were going to give us another 15 minutes, and we finally straggled in.
We ran out of money about halfway through our trip, so we were sleeping in culverts before it was over with.
But Wayne had a big influence on lots of kids,
I don't think any of us can explain what it was about that group that got into politics.
Let's see.
MSC during your four years.
What was the MSC?
What role did it play on the campus?
It was a huge role.
I think one of the reasons that you have
the kind of spirit participation, leadership training, stuff like that.
One of the reasons that kids come out is that the MSC here has always been so much bigger than at any other university.
It's not just a place to go bowling.
I mean, there are hundreds and hundreds of organizations, as you know, that these kids can join and apply leadership skills to those organizations and stuff.
And so I've tried to analyze
what it is that one of the things that makes Aggies more successful.
I mean obviously one of them is Aggies hire Aggies.
I mean I'm very guilty of that.
I mean I don't know if I ever had an Aggie apply for a job
at the controller of public accounts that isn't working at the controller of public accounts.
And I did it, of course, on merit.
And it got a little, I mean, almost to the point of embarrassment sometimes, because people would write me letters saying, the only reason I didn't get this job is I didn't have a ring.
And, you know, because of open record stuff, I wouldn't write back and say, yes, that's true.
But I think the core coupled with the MSC and so many places for kids to become involved and apply leadership skills and learn things like that is one of the reasons that kids do so well.
I think the MSC is the second academics.
It's a big part of the leadership training.
Did you ever get one of Wayne Stark's special lectures, particularly the green couch treatment?
Mm-mm.
Do you know what I mean by the green couch?
Uh-uh.
Oh, that one, for those that he thought had high capability potential but then started goofing off, he invited you down.
Remember his office was down at the end of the hallway?
At the end of the hallway.
It had that sleazy-looking green vinyl-covered couch.
He would invite you in by yourself, close the door, and put you on that couch.
And when you got through hearing the lecture he gave you, you never forgot it.
And what it really was, he would say, shame on you.
You can do better, and you know you can.

Not long ago, I was asking this in a group of people of your vintage and older and some of today's students, and when I asked, did he ever try the green couch treatment on you, three or four of today's co-eds gasped because they thought I was referring to some other kind of treatment.
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.
No, I never got that one.
I would...
I'd go down... My office was...
kind of down the stairs past the desk down there where the student president's office was and I'd go down there and shoot the breeze with Wayne and that's not a five minute deal.
That's right, that's right.
And talk to him and stuff like that, but I wasn't in, my niche wasn't in the MSC governance part of it, it was in the student senate part of it.
A tiny little thing about MSC, where did you and your buddies go for a break during the day?
MSC, the only place to go.
Yeah, went in there and it was a good hiding place for freshmen.
Go sit in those couches and stuff like that.
It was kind of a standing room.
Nobody mess with you in the Memorial Student Center and stuff like that.
Were you part of SCONA?
You weren't, were you?
No, I went to just to, I didn't do any organizing for it.
I went to some of the meetings and, you know, helped get speakers and stuff like that, but that was it.
That's your phone.
Oh, no.
Oh, I thought I heard it.
Let's see, YMCA was nothing in terms of importance during your year, was it?
Because before MSCC, the YMCA... Yeah, no, it had, it coordinated fish camp, that's the best I could tell.
Did you ever get sick and go to the quack shack, the hospital?
Yeah.
What was it like, describe the quack shack?
Oh, man, it was appropriately named.
I think my senior year they built a new one, but before that it was, you come out a lot sicker than you went in.
It was a pretty depressing little place.
I hurt myself in rugby, and that was the only time that I went there.
My junior year I was on the rugby team, and I don't know what I did.
I cracked some vertebrae or something in my neck or something like that, and after I went to the
I was walking when I went into Quack Shack.
When I came out of Quack Shack, I had to call my dad and say, you gotta get me to Victoria.
And I was out of school for a week and went down there.
I'm sure it wasn't anything that Quack Shack did, but they damn sure didn't do anything to help it.
It was located up near the... Yeah, it was down here kind of across from Sabeasa or somewhere in here.
Was there a full-time campus doctor or do you remember?
I don't think I ever saw a doctor in there.
There was a couple of nurses and stuff.
Let's see.
Gine Hall was demolished during your student days.
Well, I saw the first ball hit Gine Hall.
Really?
I watched it happen.
There was a big fence around it.
That's where the speech classes were.
The guy that announced the football games, what was his name?
Oh, oh.
Good afternoon, football fans.
Welcome to Kyle Field, home of the fighting Texas Aggies.
I took a couple of speech courses from him.
Eastern accent.
Yeah.
That's where his offices were in the back of that, but there was a big fence around it, and they had to demolish Guy Hall, I guess, to make room for Rudder Tower.
and it was a big deal.
They said at 10 o'clock in the morning the first ball is going to hit Gine Hall.
They'd already taken some bricks off and I think they had sold them or something and that wrecking ball just went pow and we watched the first one hit.
The student body, when you were here, describe the student body in general.
Attitudes, background, and so forth.
Well, let me describe it in terms of campus politics because that's what I knew best, I guess.
But you had a, in campus politics, you had a natural alliance between the core, Walton Hall, Hart Hall, Fowler to some extent, some of those old halls.
And it all hinged around the bonfire because there were certain dormitories that just bore, you know, civilian dormitories that are hell-bent for leather.
Boy, they have real serious roles.
And whether that's true now, I don't know.
But it was certainly true back then.
And so you had, because of that once-a-year deal, you had outfits in the Corps that were closely aligned with Walton Hall or closely aligned with Hart Hall and some of those.
The student body, even back then, was just starting to become urban and suburban.
I would say the core was still very rural, certainly in my dormitory it was.
If they were from the cities, they were from San Antonio.
Liberal, conservative, and basically... Oh, conservative.
Against McGovern, Nixon got 89% of the campus vote.
Very conservative.
Their values.
I remember Jerry Geisweier gave a speech one time in the middle, well, let me give you an idea of how conservative this student body was.
Kent State, the student senate was not debating whether or not to fly the half, to flag half staff as other universities were for the students killed at Kent State.
They were debating whether or not to fly the flag at half staff for the National Guardman that was wounded.
There was no sentiment in the Student Senate to fly the half-staff for those commie pinkos in Kent State.
I mean, that was the attitude.

And during that time, when there was turmoil in the late 60s, early 70s on other campuses, primarily the Vietnam War, Jerry Goswine, who was student vice president at the time, got up and gave a speech at a Mother's Day crowd
And I remember he called A&M the last bastion of sanity.
And Geisweit got more press off that worldwide than anybody could imagine.
Of course, the former students in the administration, Dean Hannigan in particular, he thought that was the best thing in the world.
But that was Geisweit's claim to glory.
The way Geisweit got to be student body president is Gary Morrow ran for student body president against Al Reiner.
Al Reinert, who wrote this screenplay for Apollo 13.
Al, grades were bad, and they didn't find out until later.
And so rather than make Gary student body president, they just nullified the election.
The election commission was controlled by the Corps.
Geisweit had won vice president, so they put Geisweit up against Morrow.
Geisweit beat Morrow for student body president, and that's how he became student president.
Because Ryder won the election.
He won the election.
He was on core staff.
He was a junior on core staff.
All right, let's see.
What about their attitude about hard work?
Hard work?
The student body.
Yeah, I think they all kind of came with that.
I mean, it was...
Geographic origin.
You said they're small town.
Lots of small town.
Income level, family income.
Couldn't have been very high.
diversity as we now use that term?
Hey, we're working hard at it, but it wasn't very.
I mean, I know in, I know there were very few Hispanics, very few blacks in the Corps or on campus.
There were a lot of Asian kids.
Remember there were a couple of dormitories of Asian kids, but most of them were from overseas

uh hotard hall several halls like that but but um there were there weren't uh too many that they kind of started working on that i think about my junior or senior year the student government was heavily involved in prayer do you remember there was a bunch of debate um morrow in particular and a guy named ken windler and austin are all trying to get the a m board to give more money to prairie view that was kind of a cause for the
for the few liberals that were on campus, you know.
But it, and that later on in the legislature got them in trouble.
Wilhelmina Delco really started taking them to task, but you talk about done good.
I mean, I think even Wilhelmina will say now that A&M is better in that regard than virtually any university you can name in the state of Texas.
Do you remember any incidents in the dormitories or in the hallways of the classroom buildings involving ethnicity and or a woman student?
Women students.
Such as?
Well, I mean, stuff that you would never tolerate now.
I mean, when a woman walked in the quadrangle of the core between 1968 and 1972, that was a major event.
very closely linked to the Second Coming.
And people would scream and holler and...
But was it a holler of approval or disapproval?
I suppose it's how she took it.
Oh, no, it was like, look at this.
You haven't seen one of these in a while.
All this kind of stuff.
But, yeah, I'm talking about not just women students walking on.
I'm talking about any woman that walks down there.
I'm sure that doesn't happen now.
If it did now, it would be, but it was just such a rare event.
I mean, women, when I graduated, there were 700 women, more than half of which were married, and about 14,000 students, something like that.
Am I correct in saying to people that black students, Hispanic students, minorities of all sorts,
had almost no problems here.
No.

I think you are correct in that regard except on San Jacinto Day and Pearl Harbor Day because in Pearl Harbor Day I remember they would go get every Asian student in the Corps and dump them in a whole groat hole somewhere
Even if they were not Japanese, American?
Well, it doesn't matter.
Anywhere close.
And everybody laughed about it, including them.
They all thought that was... And then the Hispanics on San Jacinto Day?
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, or anything like that.
Or some day like that.
I imagine if school had been going on on June the 16th or 19th, they would have had the same thing there.
That's the only thing I can remember.
They may get carried away and find some Bohemian holiday and get all of us who are Czech orientation looking for an excuse to do it.
I think that is an accurate statement.
There weren't very many, but the black and Hispanic and minority kids
nobody saw the difference.
Maybe one of the reasons for that is when you're going through that hell your first semester of your freshman year, the last thing you want to worry about is what color or background some guy has.
You're just trying to survive this thing and generally the black guy next to you is trying to survive too.
Is that the key to understanding the Aggie mentality that you're either an Aggie or you're not and if you are that's all that matters?
I think so.
It does.
All those old former students had told us when we were students that this will carry on afterward.
It does.
So your mother was a Czech ancestry, so what?
From the point of view that I've come from, and that is the core, I think

probably the army or war or things like that are the same as once you go through it together it doesn't much matter I remember when the war was over with my father you know talked about two Hispanic guys can't remember their name that when he was wounded ran out and pulled him out of the field of fire and he said oh you'll never hear me say anything bad about about a
a Mexican-American because it wouldn't be here if there weren't for those two.
Let's see, in terms of the student body makeup, what about wheels?
Who had a car and what kind of cars?
Oh, we had one kid named K.T.
Alexander from Louisiana whose family had money.
He stayed a year and decided that the LSU fraternity was where he wanted to be but he had a car.
There were very few kids
I'm trying to think if we were allowed cars.
I think freshmen were, but there was a fish parking lot.
Now, there were some kids that had cars.
There just wasn't anybody.
